  "text": "A multi-dimensional matrix of indicators was selected to represent each domain. All indicators included in the analysis are converted to standardize Z-scores to avoid scale dependence. A maximum likelihood factor analysis was then used to derive a single factor score for each domain. The motivation for using maximum likelihood factor analysis is that in most vulnerability analysis indices are based on addition. However, variables used to quantify vulnerability in most cases are highly corrected and therefore adding them up introduces a bias of double counting due to multi-colinearity [CITATION_1] . Factors analysis circumvents the problem of multi-colinearity. The factor scores generated were then ranked, scaled to the range (0, 1), by R where R = 1/N for the least sensitive/least adaptive community and R = N/N for the most sensitive/most adaptive community; N being the number of town/villages in the basin.",
  "correct_citation": {
